            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XVIII.R14</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Ever downward, always downward</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-a3f67d18-7fff-7e99-68a5-bcc14fa22685\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">See LD.XVIII.R6 for Dickens&rsquo;s use of the language of &ldquo;downward&rdquo; in this Note. In the opening of this chapter, we see Clennam&rsquo;s spirits &ldquo;sunk&rdquo; so low &ldquo;that the weight under which he bent was bearing him down,&rdquo; with the result that &ldquo;his health was sinking&rdquo; (LD 733).&nbsp;</p>"
